This Korean city has long been a hub for Japanese connections. In the nineteenth century it served as Japanese merchants’ primary access point to Asian trade networks. When it opened, Busan’s Japanese-run telegraph station became an equally important gateway. It handled all Korean telegraph traffic until an overland link to Seoul was completed in 1888, and it allowed Japanese-language telegrams to leave the country for the first time. Cable traffic spiked from a few thousand messages sent between the two countries in 1884 to some 430,000 — the vast majority in Japanese. In 1931, Busan was the site of Japanese experiments for another communications revolution: the use of undersea cables for voice transmission. Today, the city’s two cable stations, which provide a major gateway to the Internet, are finally operated by Korean companies. Yet the country faces another challenge at its shores – from local aquaculture rather than foreign powers. Dense seaweed forests immediately off Busan’s coast twist around ropes bordering the cable’s path. Harvesting the seaweed, fishermen come dangerously close to the country’s international communications lines. Whenever cable companies land a new system, they have to be careful not to disturb the fragile seaweed’s growth. Each cable must be carefully placed in a “mattress” before it is lowered down into the crop.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: At the request of the Japanese government, the Great Northern Telegraph Company laid the first cable under the Korean Strait in 1883. The cable linked Nagasaki via Japan’s Tsushima Island to Pusan (now officially spelled Busan), the first international port in Korea and a major Japanese settlement.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 1933 the Japanese government laid a cable across the Sea of Japan, linking Tsushima with mainland Korea. At this time Korea was formally annexed by Japan, yet host to an insurgent provisional government that was fighting to resist Japanese control. The cable’s implementation followed a series of repressive Japanese policies targeting public communications, including the banning of the Korean language from schools and newspapers.
Completed in 1980 by Japan’s KDDI Corporation, this coaxial system linked Hamada and Pusan. It was decommissioned in 1997 and donated to the Ocean Research Institute at Tokyo University.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 1995, this optical line replaced the coaxial Japan Sea Cable between Japan and Russia, increasing capacity more than 300-fold and adding a link to Korea. Over a dozen companies invested in the project, including KDDI (Japan), Rostelecom (Russia), and AT&T. The cable fell out of use when the new Russia-Japan Cable Network came online in 2008.

When it was completed in December 1937, the submarine cable between Fukuoka and Pusan became part of the longest carrier telephone line in service. From Fukuoka, the six-channel cable ran over the Japanese mainland to Tokyo, and from Pusan, it extended north through Korea and into the Manchukuo region of China, covering a total of more than 2,000 miles. The cable not only improved the quality of commercial telephone calls between Japan and the continent, but also expanded Japanese military communications in the lead-up to the Second World War.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: For decades, Taiwan’s cables have been concentrated at its northern and southern tips. While the Tanshui and Toucheng stations are on the fringes of Taipei, the Chunghwa Telecom station is located in the rural southern township of Fangshan. Most traffic to Southeast Asia, whether from Taiwan, East Asia, or North America, passes through the Bashi Strait, the narrow passage separating Taiwan and the Philippines. Fangshan was the ideal gateway to this route until recently, when a spate of natural disasters severed numerous cable links. An earthquake in September 1999 broke Taiwan’s terrestrial backbone, one undersea cable, and caused cell sites and radio relays to collapse. During the 2006 Hengchun earthquake, submarine landslides took out nine undersea links. Most recently, Typhoon Morakot disrupted six international cables and 1,700 wireless base stations, in addition to taking 500 lives. Fangshan, perched on the edge of the Bashi Strait, is no longer a popular interconnection point for undersea traffic.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: From the Batam cable station, you look out across rusty brown sand and a dark blue sea. Somewhere across that water is Singapore, where the far end of the cable has landed since 2006. The station shares the shore with many other industries. Silhouettes of cranes and oil rigs rise up against the landscape. Not much farther along the coast are ship-repair yards and ferry ports. Fiber-optic signals run underneath, supporting the large-scale transfer of goods and people to and from Singapore. Part of a free trade zone, the whole area is quite lassiez-faire. The city exerts relatively little control over the information, commerce, and people that stream in and out. This is in stark contrast to Indonesia's policy for cable ships: to repair systems in coastal seas, cable companies have to apply for permits, and might wait months before being granted access.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Tseung Kwan O, known in English as “Junk Bay” for the many fishing boats that once dotted its waters, is now a booming tech center. As is true for much of urban Hong Kong, this area is built upon reclaimed land and the nearby Tseung Kwan O Industrial Estate extends over fill where the bay used to be. The Industrial Estate, one of many set up by the Hong Kong Science & Technology Parks Corporation, is the headquarters of Hong Kong's largest television broadcaster. It also houses the content of a significant slice of the Hong Kong Internet: twelve major data centers are located here, including those of HSBC, the Japanese firm NTT Communications, and Telehouse Hong Kong. Signals transit in and out of the data centers to destinations around the world via four submarine cables that land here. Behind the Industrial Estate, however, in the enormous South East New Territories landfill, the debris of such accelerated flows remain.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Before Hong Kong was handed back to China, one author observed that it was a “center of espionage, a hive of spies,” with up to 5,000 intelligence agents seeking information for countries around the world. In 1977, the British GCHQ built a satellite base at Chung Hom Kok, on Hong Kong’s less populated southern coast. For over a decade, the satellite base, code-named “Project Kittiwake,” was a center for monitoring Chinese communications and nuclear tests. It was scanned communications about events such as the Tiananmen Square massacre in 1989 and the break-up of the Soviet Union in 1991. When Hong Kong was transferred back to China, Project Kittiwake was moved and the site razed, leaving little for the Chinese to see. At the turn of the century, the Chinese government invested in Chung Hom Kok’s external communications – it was designated a “telecentre” for the development of satellite and submarine connections. Today a new undersea cable station, poised on the edge of a hill and overlooking small fishing boats that dot the waters, still monitors traffic. Rather than intercepting signals sent through the air, communications are now filtered before they are allowed to enter mainland China.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Propelled by a strong wind, you land on a small, white sand beach dotted with coconut palms and volcanic rock formations in the southern part of Tutulia Island. This spot is now linked to Hawai'i by underwater cable, but the same connection was once made by air. During World War II, the U.S. Navy built an airfield here, which was later converted to receive passenger jets. By the 1960s, it had become a key stopping point for flights between Australia and Hawai‘i. As planes grew larger in the 1980s, however, they started to land at the expanded airport in nearby Samoa or bypass the islands entirely, no longer needing to refuel midway along their journeys. Today, the runways are mostly used by military and cargo transports with only the occasional passenger flight, making the U.S. territory feel remote. The cable didn’t do much to change this, since few locals can afford the steep Internet fees.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Here, you land on Back Beach, amidst a strip of towering upscale hotels, small seafood restaurants, and military installations left over from the American War. From the cable’s landing point, you move under the temporary infrastructure of beach chairs and food carts that support weekenders from Saigon, past the bunker-like buildings that fortress the beach, and inland to the VTI cable station in the center of Vung Tau, identifiable by its huge radio tower. Behind the cable station, a statue of a woman holding a cell phone brings the site good luck. For many years, indeed, Vung Tau has been lucky: since the United States military landed their first undersea telephone on Back Beach, subsequent cables have been drawn to this spot, from the TVH cable in 1993 to the TGN Intra-Asia cable in 2009. Yet the latest link, the Asia-America Gateway cable, has not been so fortunate. Since its initiation it has been cut several times, severely affecting internet traffic in Vietnam.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Built in the 1970s, the Nanhui station was the first landing site for international coaxial cables in China. Early signals surfaced on the muddy shores of Nanhui district, then mostly farmland, roughly thirty miles southeast of central Shanghai. Now the area is almost unrecognizable, transformed by rapid industrialization that has displaced many of its former inhabitants. Large-scale development projects have even altered the local geography, continuing a process begun millennia ago when Nanhui was formed by silt deposited at the mouth of the Yangtze River. New cables pass by a huge artificial island that contains the recently constructed Shanghai deep-water container port, linked to the mainland by a twenty-mile bridge. And just east of the station, an entire city for 800,000 is being built from scratch on land reclaimed from Hangzhou Bay.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: C-J FOSC, laid in 1993 for $70 million dollars, was the first fiber-optic undersea system connecting mainland China to the rest of the world. From its landing point in Miyazaki, Japan, it linked outward to much of Southeast Asia. Although this gave China connectivity, it made the nation highly dependent on one Japanese hub.

The KDDI-owned East China Sea Cable, also know as the Japan-China cable system, linked Reihoku and Nanhui in 1976. A commemorative silver coin shows a dotted line across the East China Sea, bisected by a telephone receiver emitting bolts of electricity. Its 480-voice-channel capacity was interrupted in 1980 by fishing operations and not repaired until five years later. ECSC was eventually decommissioned in 1997.

Popular with surfers and backpackers, the small fishing village of Cherating lies approximately twenty miles north of Kuantan on the central east coast of Malaysia. Every spring and summer, leatherback sea turtles swim through the calm waters and lay their eggs on broad sand beaches lined with Casuarina trees. These same environmental conditions are well suited to underwater cable landings: sand is an accommodating medium for cable burial and there are no strong ocean currents to shift or expose cables once in place. Although cables have connected here since the 1980s, the current station was built as part of Telekom Malaysia’s investment in the APCN-2 system of the early 2000s. A single-story complex with pitched roofs set back from the road and surrounded by a security fence, the Cherating cable station is relatively unassuming. But a large communications tower, visible for miles, marks the site as a hub for signal traffic.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/bibliographicCi.value: Source: “Three-way Link-up launched,” New Straits Times, 28 September 1983: 2.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Surfacing at Sinduri beach, Taean, you may think you’ve been transported to the shores of California or Australia. In fact, Sinduri is home to Korea’s only sand dunes, formed thousands of years ago by winds sweeping inland from the sea. The grains still have trace amounts of oil from a massive spill in 2007, roughly one-third the size of the Exxon Valdez disaster. Set back from the beach on a small peninsula, Sinduri’s cable station received its first fiber-optic link in 1996, but it was not until the arrival of the East Asia Crossing cable a few years later that the only landing site on Korea’s west coast became a hub in a major international network.

The CKC (China-Korea Cable), completed in 1996 and since decommissioned, was the first underwater optical telephone cable to connect China and Korea. Its opening was commemorated by a Chinese postage stamp featuring a blue and green map of the two landing sites at Qingdao and Taean. The sites are marked by silhouettes of traditional buildings and are joined by a thin red line. A brightly colored cable, complete with pulsing light waves and a metallic signal repeater, runs across the bottom of the stamp.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You arrive at a cable station fit for a king. Constructed for the landing of a new fiber-optic network, one cable industry leader recalls that the Tungku station was “built as a palace” so that it could be inaugurated by the Sultan of Brunei. In the following years, the massive station would become a hub of links to Singapore, Malaysia, and the Philippines, followed by connections reaching as far as the U.S. and Western Europe. When a link to the Asia-America Gateway in 2009 created an oversupply of bandwidth, the Brunei government sold it to international carriers in order to finance new cable landings. Located a few miles north of the capital, the station is at once remote and central, surrounded by trees but also a highway exchange and the campuses of both the University of Brunei and an international boarding school. Across the street, a fifteen-story glass office tower (and the second tallest building in the country) contains the headquarters of local telecom provider DataStream Technology Group. When cables first arrived on nearby Tungku Beach in the 1990s, illegal sand mining had caused severe erosion. But the jagged shoreline has been restored and is now a popular place for watching sunsets.

This cable was launched on October 19, 1992, with a press conference at the Philippine Plaza Hotel in Manila. It was part of the $320 million ASEAN Optical-Fiber Submarine Cable Network, which also included lines between Brunei and Singapore, and between two parts of Malaysia across the South China Sea.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Landing at one of two designated sites on the northern and southern coasts of Changi, you make your way inland to a cluster of stations that form East Singapore’s primary cable hub. Today, the area is known for its major international airport complex, which includes a cactus garden, butterfly habitat, and what will soon be the world’s largest indoor waterfall. But this cutting-edge cable and aviation crossroads has a dark history. The British established a military base at Changi in the early 1900s when the peninsula was still mostly swampland and forests of tall “chengei” trees. During its occupation of Singapore in World War II, Japan used the compound to imprison thousands of captured Allied soldiers. (The prison was rebuilt in the 1990s and now has a death-row detention center). Even the northern beaches where cables come ashore, a popular spot for picnics and watersports, were the setting for a brutal 1942 massacre of Chinese Singaporeans thought to be anti-Japanese.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Shima is a major hub with connections to five active international cable networks and three different cable stations, but it remains largely invisible to local residents. While cables are hidden, several festivals call attention to the surrounding ocean, known for its abundant marine life since at least the eighth century. Every June, a twenty-foot wooden spiny lobster is paraded through the city streets to encourage a bountiful harvest season. And in September, four men carry an oversized waraji (traditional straw sandal) into the ocean, setting it adrift. This ritual is designed to ward off Dandarabocchi, a mythological giant so large that his footsteps create lakes. Afterwards, spectators gather on the beach for dancing and a fireworks display.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Oxford Falls is a center of coordination, a place where seemingly opposed forces depend on one another: human and non-human, wired and wireless, and major telecommunications competitors. A relatively rural area north of Sydney, Oxford Falls was a satellite gateway well before it was a hub for wired infrastructure. In 1987, the government-owned Overseas Telecommunication Commission selected this valley for a satellite earth station in part because the surrounding forest, densely vegetated with native species, naturally protected aerial signals from radiointerference. Eight years later, the earth station’s major competitor, Optus, set up a second facility just down the road. As nature shielded human communication and as competitors paved the way for one another, wireless forms also set the stage for wired links. In the years that followed, major international cable networks terminated in Oxford Falls, interconnecting with rather than eliminating the older satellite arrays.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Combined with the Tasman 2 and PacRim East cables, PacRim West provided a link between Australia, New Zealand, and existing transpacific networks. To do so, it even had to traverse the Mariana Trench near the coast of Guam. Completed in 1995, its data capacities were designed for an early age of Internet use, but proved inadequate just a few years later. The cable was decommissioned in 2005 and recycled to become part of the APNG-2 network.

You make your way through sludge and silt to come ashore – quite a different experience from the clear seawater of the southern Japanese islands. A Spanish and then Dutch colony in the seventeenth century, Tanshui (also known as Dansheui) grew to become the largest port in Taiwan by the late 1800s. Coal and tea were exported in vast quantities from the natural harbor where the Tanshui River meets the Strait of Taiwan. In 1887, an underwater telegraph cable joined the bustling city to Fuzhou on the Chinese mainland, and a year later the Taipei Telegraph Academy opened nearby. But in the early twentieth century, the buildup of silt at the river mouth caused much of the shipping traffic to move east to Keelung. While its port status dwindled, Tanshui retained its position as an international cable hub. Several fiber-optic systems arrived in the early 2000s, linking the town to points throughout East Asia and the Pacific. Twin landing stations, owned by competing telecom carriers, are situated along a quiet beach west of the city, famous for vivid sunsets and a popular leisure destination for residents of Taipei.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: By the 1990s, capacity was filling up at Hong Kong’s major cable station, and the cable companies looked for a place to expand. Lantau Island, just west of the city of Hong Kong, seemed ideal. It was to be the site for major infrastructure developments during that period: a new international airport, a trans-bay expressway, and the AsiaWorld theme park were placed in what was otherwise a sprawling, sparsely populated jungle. The station builders chose Tong Fuk for their landing, a small village on the island’s southern shore. When they went to construct the station, however, the village leaders resisted, worried that the cable stations would disrupt the feng shui of the land and bring them bad fortune. The stations were ultimately placed there, but companies careful not to infringe upon the nearby shrine.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You arrive in Baccuit Sur, a coastal neighborhood in the town of Bauang, near resorts, dive shops, and stands that sell grapes and guava-apple hybrids from local farms. The two main segments of the Asia-America Gateway fiber-optic system meet at Bauang’s cable station, forming a bridge between Southeast Asia and the Pacific. Before it catered to beachgoers and network traffic, this former Spanish colony was a site of violent conflict. Moro pirates invaded Bauang several times in the 1800s, leading the town to construct a defensive network of cylindrical stone watchtowers along the coast. And when Japan occupied the Philippines during the Second World War, Japanese troops clashed with the local resistance movement on Bauang’s otherwise calm shores.

You speed ashore on the Asia Submarine-cable Express, landing two miles outside the city of Daet, in a small coastal village popular for its kite-surfing and aquatic sports. From the broad, sandy beach, you move up an elevated promenade that protects the village from storm surges during typhoons. To the left is an aging airport runway, repurposed in between flights as a jogging and cycling path. Turning right, you reach the modern landing station, owned by the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company. When it was connected in 2012, the cable was framed as a benefit for both international exchange (it offers the most direct communication route to Japan) and the local economy. After touring the station with a group of Japanese officials, Daet’s mayor praised its attractiveness to companies that wished to develop call centers, one of the fastest-growing industries in the Philippines.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 2008, Qingdao hosted the sailing regatta for the Beijing Olympic Games. Teams from forty countries navigated a racecourse in the Yellow Sea, not far from where underwater cables surface in Fushan Bay. To realize its vision of a “Broadband Olympics,” China Netcom extended the East Asia Crossing cable to its Qingdao landing station at the same time. While the Olympics may have prompted this connection, there are other reasons to bring cables here. China’s northernmost hub, Qingdao lies midway between the financial centers of Beijing and Shanghai. Compared to hubs in South China, it offers more direct access to networks spanning Korea, Japan, and the United States. Even in the colonial era, the port was coveted for its strategic location. Germany kept a naval base outside the city, then called Tsingtau, until Japan seized control at the start of World War I.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: The Telekom Malysia (TM) cable landing station at Mersing is situated on an otherwise undeveloped beach roughly six miles south of the town center. Large signage on a curved, blue glass awning and a flag bearing the TM logo ensure that the site is highly visible from the coastal highway that passes nearby. Since the late 1990s, it has housed cables linking southeastern Malaysia to the rest of Asia, the U.S., the Middle East, and Western Europe. On their journey east, these cables intersect the offshore Seribuat Archipelago, for which Mersing’s ferry terminal is the main point of departure. As Malays, tourists, and communication signals are carried out to sea, north-south trade routes link Mersing to the rest of the Malay Peninsula as a site of tin, rubber, and palm oil production.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: From your landing place on Ajigaura Beach, the ocean seems to blur into the landscape. But what appear to be rolling waves are actually the hills of Hitachi Seaside Park covered with more than four million blue flowers, a spring spectacle that attracts thousands of visitors. These nemophilas also grow in the western U.S., which has been connected to Ajigaura by submarine cable since 2000. The park shares its name with the Hitachi electronics company, in turn named after a local copper mine that was once the largest in Japan. In the early nineteenth century, it spurred great industrial development, likely providing the raw material for copper telegraph cables, but also damaged crops and forests with air pollution. Hitachi established a cable division in the 1950s and went on to manufacture several underwater networks, including portions of TPC-5 and the Guam-Philippines cable.

Sri Racha is an industrial economic center in the province of Chonburi, about an hour’s drive from Bangkok on an eight-lane freeway. Rice, sugar, rubber, tapioca, coconut, and seafood are all produced in vast quantities before being exported from Laem Chabang, the largest container port in Thailand and one of the busiest commercial harbors in the world. Shipping lines dovetail with the paths of underwater cables that link Sri Racha to other communication hubs in Southeast Asia and across the Pacific. Most of the district’s beaches are muddy and rocky, with development often reaching the water’s edge. But cables land on one of the few slivers of sand in the area north of Laem Chabang before making their way inland past factories and manufacturing plants to the state-owned cable station.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Shantou is a hub in four international cable networks, all built since the late 1990s. From your point of arrival on Longhu Beach, this state-of-the-art China Telecom facility could be mistaken for one of the many resort hotels that line the waterfront. Yet the new technology and luxury tourism of Shantou lies only twenty miles from Guiyu, a town that has been called “the electronic-waste capital of the globe.” Every year, the city receives over 1.5 million pounds of discarded computers and other electronics, most of it from overseas. Tens of thousands of laborers strip cables and dismantle circuit boards to extract valuable metals, but the toxic byproducts of these machines have devastated the workers’ health and surrounding environment.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: In 1900, the village of Naic in Cavite Province was joined to an offshore island by underwater telegraph cable as part of a U.S. Army Signal Corps operation to network the area around Manila. A century later, Naic became a landing site for EAC-C2C, bringing it into direct communication with the U.S. and several Asian countries. Owned by the Philippine Long Distance Telephone Company (PLDT), the station is located on the town’s outskirts near farmland, subdivisions, and a vast new horseracing complex with stables for 800 thoroughbreds. Even though they are broadcast online, spectators travel from as far as Manila to witness the races first-hand, a popular activity in the Philippines since the late nineteenth century. Some have even described the local telecommunications market, dominated by PLDT and Globe Telecom, as a two-horse race.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: While many cable hubs remain concealed, the Melaka landing station is exceptionally visible. The large, sky-blue building towers over the houses in Pengkalan Balak, roughly fifteen miles north of central Melaka. A flag and bright signage mark the gated entryway. Following a series of Internet outages caused by high-profile earthquakes, Telekom Malaysia invited journalists to tour its station in order to expand awareness of the undersea network. A video of the tour documents the beach landing site, vast battery banks, a computerized control center, and the underground “cable chamber” where fiber lines enter the station. In the chamber, a reporter gestures to a bundle of black cables tagged “NOTICE: SeaMeWe-4 Cable System,” surprisingly physical evidence that the Melaka station carries much of Malaysia’s signal traffic to Europe.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: A futuristic cable station sits next to the expansive wetlands of the Dongtan national wildlife sanctuary. Signals arrive through major underwater networks, while swans, cranes, spoonbills, shorebirds, and many species of fish stop here along their migratory routes. Like the landing station, Chongming Island’s salt-water marshes and tidal flats are transitional zones that mediate between land and sea. Although it feels rural, the island is only twenty miles from central Shanghai and is connected by a freeway. Visitors fill the tree-lined boardwalks that crisscross the reserve, observing the local fauna. Meanwhile, data is surveilled as it passes through the station: a white sign with red text marks the presence of underground cables and bears the name “PLA Unit 61398,” a group believed to engage in electronic monitoring and cyber-attacks against the United States.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Past meets present in this northern district of New Taipei City, the vast municipality that surrounds Taiwan’s capital. Traditional Chinese sailing junks are constructed in a small shipyard adjacent to a huge, modern container port, built in the 1990s and early 2000s. Rice and peanuts are harvested by hand on the moist foothills of Guanyin Mountain while a local amusement park attracts visitors with one of the longest water slides in the region. At the same time that Pa Li (also known as Bali) is networked in space through shipping channels and a branch of the East Asia Crossing cable system, it is also connected across time. A museum of archeology showcases artifacts from Taiwan’s earliest inhabitants, unearthed during recent development. It includes a display called the “Bridge of Time,” which allows museumgoers to imaginatively visit a prehistoric Taiwanese culture that once thrived in the area.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: You can journey to the village of Maruyama along cables from the U.S., Australia, or various sites in Southeast Asia. But upon reaching the station, you may feel as if you’ve traveled even farther—and back in time. Across the road is Rosemary Park, a detailed replica of a sixteenth-century English town. Built in 1997 by British architects, the tourist attraction includes a working windmill, formal gardens, a duck pond, and a recreation of Shakespeare’s childhood home, complete with lifelike statues and time-specific furnishings. Shakespeare referenced rosemary in his plays, and Maruyama is known for producing this and other herbs. While the park looks to the past, the modern cable station is one of Japan’s most popular landing sites. Both enact a kind of virtual transit to far-off locales.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Kitaibaraki thrived as a center of coal mining in the nineteenth century, with rail lines connecting it to Tokyo a hundred miles away. In 2011, a 9.0-magnitude earthquake devastated the city. The closest cable station to the epicenter, Kitaibaraki was severed from both the U.S. and Asian networks, though Japan’s cable density allowed much of the traffic to be rerouted. The tsunami also wiped out an important cultural landmark: a red pagoda-like meditation retreat designed by Japanese philosopher and art historian Tenshin Okakura. While this structure was rebuilt in its original location on the rocky shores of the Pacific Ocean, cable operator KDDI announced the construction of a new tsunami-resistant station in Chikura that will stand ninety feet above sea level.

http://rdfs.org/sioc/ns#content.value: Since the 1880s, Chikura has been known for precision exercises tied to the ocean. Every year, a knife ceremony is held at a local shrine dedicated to the gods of seasoning and culinary arts. Seven or eight men fillet and plate a whole carp using nothing but a twenty-inch blade and a pair of foot-long chopsticks, honoring the town’s legacy as a fishing community. In 1989, Chikura became a site of underwater cable innovation. The first fiber-optic line between the U.S. and Japan landed here, less than fifty miles from central Tokyo, followed by many other cables in the 1990s and 2000s. More recently, the town has become a surfing hub. Several professional competitions are held on Setohama Beach, where well-formed waves crash opposite the prominent cable station.
